defaultcall indefault and hear from the 
defaultTraffic Commisdefaultsionersdefault on how they can act to regulate the use of HGV’s and deliver their objective to ’prevent harm’ from the operation of commercial vehicles.
default&#xa0;
default9default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Investigation of Rail Crashes (Rail Accident Investigation Branch). defaultThis system delivers an non judgement
defaultal report, which is transparently available in the public domain. The reports list the sequence of events, and their outcomes, and quantify the details of the vehicles, and people involved and the various site measurements, followed by an analysis of the c
defaultausal factors and hazards relating to the incident, concluding with a list of recommendations to prevent a recurrence.
default&#xa0;default10default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt doesn’t always deliver perfectly – notably the issue of single lead junctions, where a crash at Bellgrove in Glasgow was followed 2 y
defaultears later by a similar crash at Newton before the need to provide a more positive measures, or eliminate the arrangement at the junctions where it had been designed in.  However the road crash equivalent is just not of a matching standard.
default&#xa0;default11default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA road crash m
defaultay be investigated by Police or an Insurer but these reports are not automatically published, and will generally have the objective of identifying one or more of the parties involved in the crash as being liable for prosecution or providing recompense to o
defaultthers who suffer loss or injury.  There is no clear setting out of the hazard(s) at the root of the crash, and the risk management (or failure of the risk management systems) that played their part in the crash under investigation. There is no clearly spel
defaultled out action to prevent recurrence of the same type of crash, which a roads authority should consider for implementation.
default&#xa0;default12default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs a result of this even a brief trawl of incidents that were known to me, over the past 13 years, brought up 2 examples of where a
default basic hazard as not been eliminated, and risk management regimes are clearly inadequate
default&#xa0;default13default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultExample 1) the left turn from the offside lane across ALL traffic travelling in the nearside lane – from a brief check in minimal detail 5 identical circumstances whe
defaultre for keeping speed up or the basic lack of space the truck or bus/coach driver has made a left turn from a traffic lane designated for vehicles travelling straight ahead. In only one case I have checked was action taken to remove the hazard (Ellie Carey 
default– killed December 2011, and as a result, HGV left turns banned between Tower Bridge Road and Abbey Street)
default&#xa0;default14
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOf the 6 deaths in November both Richard Muzira and Francis Golding died when a truck driver approached the junction in an offside lane and cut across the nearside lane, more tellingly, the death of Francis Golding was a repeat of the death of Wan-Chen McG
defaultuinness almost exactly 5 years earlier with a large truck making the same left turn from Vernon Place in to Southampton Row from a lane over to the right hand side – signed for travelling straight ahead. Two fatalities, and potentially other near misses I’
defaultve yet to uncover shout that the large vehicles should not be permitted to make left turns at this junction, in its present layout.  Large vehicles should be sent round via High Holborn, where the space to make wider turns is available, make their Northbou
defaultnd turn at 
defaultTottenham Court Road, or the junction made suitable for large vehicles turning from the left turn lane.  
default&#xa0;
default15default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis hazard exists at many junctions across London, and the move for improving cyclist and pedestrian safety has to be a review of places 
defaultwhere the potential hazard exists, and a risk management plan for each individual location drawing on known crash reports, the conditions in which large vehicles attempt this manoeuvre, and the practical options for modifying the junction geometry, or dive
defaultrting left turning large vehicles via a safer route. I would also hope that delivery of published crash investigation reports would  highlight those locations where the greatest risk and greatest urgency for action exists in this respect.   
default&#xa0;default16default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultExample 2) Bo
defaultw roundabout. An analysis of the hazards on the CS2 route here will show that 
default100% of the motor vehicle trafficdefault circulating on this roundabout 
defaultWILL drive through the path of any cyclistsdefault using CS2 as this traffic joins or leaves the A12. From observation a
defaultround 80%, and possibly more of the motor traffic travelling on the East-West axis uses the roundabout to join or leave the A12.  Managing the risk of this motor traffic colliding with a cyclist relies entirely on the human factor detail of compliance with
default the instructions given by traffic signs and signals.  There is no fail to safe position whereby the failure to observe a signal or sign by either a driver or cyclist does not create an inevitable crash, or near miss incident.
default&#xa0;default17default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultBy contrast TfL’s own survey
default shows that around 60% of the cycle traffic actually goes over the flyover where there is almost a 0% potential for the hazard of a motor vehicle turning through the path taken by a cyclist. 
default&#xa0;default18default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe type of report required is very much set to the same templa
defaultte as used by RAIB, and HSE, for dangerous and fatal incidents where the locations are on the railway or the workplace.  HSE has for over a decade been highlighting the flawed situation where the employer and employee’s duties of care at work vanish when t
defaulthe workplace is on the public road.
default&#xa0;default19default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe HSE work notes that at least a third of road crash KSI’s are liked to use of the road as a workplace and this figure is around 10% of their annual reported KSI at work incidents.  This makes the road an area where H
defaultSE wants to deliver the safety improvements delivered on construction sites and in factories by their regime.    
default&#xa0;default20default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWith TfL committing almost £1bn to cycling I suggest that  a budget be included in this to deliver published and impartial investigation repo
defaultrts into fatal and serious cyclist and pedestrian crashes, and draw on those reports to inform and deliver on effective design which;
default&#xa0;default       identifies the hazards, 
default       eliminates those hazards where possible
default       provides an effective risk manageme
defaultnt regime when the hazards cannot be    
default       completely eliminated
default&#xa0;default21default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTo inform the Committee I would suggest that a 
defaultrepresentative from HSEdefault describes their work on management of road risks in their efforts to get the safety culture of the workplace extended to embrace the use of the road as a workplace. Failing the HSE the RAIB could be invited to describe how their regime can be applied to r
defaultoad crashes and dangerous incidents.
default&#xa0;default22default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTruck design defaultThe recent CLoCS event had an example of a tipper truck with a low level driving position which gives direct vision between those outside and inside the cab. Not only does it enhance the safety of cyclists
default and pedestrians, but also the safety of drivers – falls from trucks with high cabs are a major source of driver injury – A PQ on this might be very informative. TfLcould introduce a requirement for such cab designs with a 5 year horizon in exactly the sam
defaulte way as they already have done for emissions, and low floor accessible buses.  Mercedes and Dennis Eagle are supplying such vehicles, and they are discussing the wider adoption of low cab designs for urban trucks with SMMT and TfL. It would be useful to h
defaultave such input to the Inquiry·
default&#xa0;default23
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTruck definitiondefault – there are vehicles which look to all intents like trucks, can weigh the maximum permitted weight of a truck and yet be driven with no operators licence, by a driver with Class C1 (standard driving licence)
default and no drivers hours regulation. the Committee should be aware of vehicles such as
default defaultMobile defaultVolumetric defaultBatching defaultPlantdefault which have been noted to be pulled over at up to 25% overweight for the chassis they are being used on.  At the same time a major legislati
defaultve change could have serious impact on specialist firms operating such vehicles and plant in a responsible way within the current system.
default&#xa0;
default24
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultReducing ton milesdefault defaultConcrete mixer trucks travel relatively short distances, but tippers are often doing 70+ mile round trips and this activity cannot be shut down. Some machinery – like Tunnel Boring Machines could seize in the bore if they stop moving forward. and produce t
defaultonnages that should be put on rail or water – we have NO serious strategy to provide railheads and wharves, and instances of promised alternatives have failed to be delivered because the co-ordination cannot be delivered for the sporadic demands of individ
defaultual developments. TfL say that they cannot, as a public body underwrite or operate such a transfer/consolidation  facility with public funds but we have the conundrum of being able to maintain such a facility for a few £’000 per year and the very unlikely 
defaultposition that a £2-£3m facility taking 2-3 years to deliver would be viable for each new project.  Reducing ton miles reduces risk, reduces pollution, reduces road damage. 
